	<text>
		<body>
			<div>
				<pb facs="#facs_1" n="1"/>
				<p facs="#facs_1_tr_1">
					<lg>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_1">Dept. of Philosophy</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_2">February 11, 1949</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_3">Dear <persName ref="gnd-116183853">Gertrud Bing</persName>:</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_4">Thank you for your letter of January 3, which I found on my return</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_5">from the <placeName ref="geo-6252001">United States</placeName>.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_6">I am replying now to two questions which you mention, that of the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_7">publication of the <ref target="https://archive.org/details/saturn-and-melancholy-studies-in-the-history-of-natural-philosophy-religion-and-art">Melancholy</ref>, and that of the printing of the Galenus.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_8">I. <ref target="https://archive.org/details/saturn-and-melancholy-studies-in-the-history-of-natural-philosophy-religion-and-art">Melancholy</ref>:</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_9">1) Title. May I say first that, at <persName ref="gnd-118804898">Saxl's</persName> suggestion, we proposed</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_10">to add a sub-title. In German, the full title was to be: <ref target="https://www.suhrkamp.de/buch/saturn-und-melancholie-t-9783518286104">Melancholie</ref>
                        </l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_11">und Saturn. Studien zur Geschichte der Religion, Naturphilosophie und</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_12">Bildenden Kunst. The English translation should take account of the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_13">sub-title, though it may well be simplified. I will write about this</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_14">another time.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_15">2) English translation: In the meantime, some friends of mine have</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_16">read the MS and would like to try to get it published. A provisional</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_17">estimate has shown that the cost of production will be very high, and</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_18">that it will hardly be possible to sell the book at less than $30.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_19">Considering this price, we cannot count on a large sale. It is clear</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_20">that a fairly substantial subvention is needed. My friends would like</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_21">to try the <orgName ref="gnd-40535-8">American Council of Learned Societies</orgName>, a representative of</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_22">which is expected here in the course of March. Also, we will ask</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_23">the advice of the President of the <orgName ref="gnd-30266-1">American Bibliographical Society</orgName>
                        </l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_24">who will lecture here on <event type="Lecture" date="1949-02-23">February 23rd</event>; he may know whether, e.g., there</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_25">is any sense in approaching the College Art Association.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_26">In April or May I hope to know if there is any chance that one of</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_27">the attempts made now will be successful. I have not yet written to</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_28">Nelson about it as he would certainly wish to have the MS, which is</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_29">still wanted here.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_30">Perhaps you could look around on your side in case any possibility</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_31">occurs to you. Would you in that case keep me informed?</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_32">Should Nelson be interested in the idea, could you perhaps let him</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_33">have the second copy of the translation? It need not be the fair copy.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_34">3) Italian translation: About ten days ago, my friend Calogero saw</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_35">a copy of the German proofs in my office. Being interested in the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_36">parts dealing with philosophy, he read the whole, and was so impressed</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_37">that he offered to write to one of the big Italian publishing firms</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_38">about it. He made the following proposal: the Italian publisher</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_39">should have a translation made at his own expense, and deduct the cost</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_40">of the translation from the royalties (a minimum of 10 percent is</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_41">usual in Italy); he added a description of the book, with his ap-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_42">preciation. The title he suggests is: <ref target="https://www.einaudi.it/catalogo-libri/arte-e-musica/arte/saturno-e-la-melanconia-fritz-sakxl-9788806550790/">Saturno e Malinconia</ref>. Storia di</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_43">un simbolo e di una idea. He posted his letter four or five days ago.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_44">Today the reply came, in form of a telegram from the Head of the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_45">Casa Einaudi (the <persName ref="gnd-119144719">son of the present President</persName> of Italy):</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_46">"GRATO PROPOSTA ACCOLTA CON ENTUSIASMO MANDI MANOSCRITTO GIULIO</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_47">EINAUDI"</l>
					</lg>
				</p>
				<pb facs="#facs_2" n="2"/>
				<p facs="#facs_2_tr_1">
					<lg>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_1">-2.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_2">I hope you will be pleased by this development. You may have seen</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_3">how well <persName ref="gnd-119144719">Einaudi</persName> produced the new complete (Italian) illustrated</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_4">edition of Thousand And One Nights, prepared by our collaborator,</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_5">Professor Gabrieli. He may be relied on to produce the <ref target="https://archive.org/details/saturn-and-melancholy-studies-in-the-history-of-natural-philosophy-religion-and-art">Melancholy</ref>
                        </l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_6">well.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_7">The only problem which has to be solved in this connection is</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_8">that of copyright. In my opinion--which, I think, you will share-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_9">the Italian edition should not prejudice the possibility of finding</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_l_2579">a publisher on this side (or in the U. K.). The arrangement at which</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_12">I should like to aim is, therefore, the following:</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_13">
                            <persName ref="gnd-119144719">Einaudi</persName> should have the book translated at his expense and publish</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_14">it. He would have no copyright--either none at all, or at least, as</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_15">far as the publication in English is concerned. In exchange, he</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_16">would have to pay no royalties whatsoever; we would only demand a</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_17">certain number of free copies.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_18">As you see from his telegram, he wants to go ahead immediately.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_19">Calogero is replying that I am consulting you with regard to the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_20">English copyright; and he will mention, tentatively, the above pro-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_21">posal.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_22">There is one further question to decide: whether the German text</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_23">or the English translation should form the basis for the Italian.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_24">This is a minor matter, but it will have to be decided soon. At</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_25">present, it will be easier for us, presumably, to spare a set of the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_26">German proofs; there should be two sets in the Institute; and</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_27">Augustine may well have kept one or two more; could you perhaps ask</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_28">him to send them to you? The German text has the further advantage</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_29">that all Latin and Greek quotations have been corrected, at least in</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_30">my own set and, I believe, in one of yours. (Mr. Buchthal, at the time,</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_31">entered my corrections in his own set). Would you be so kind as to</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_32">let me know as soon as possible whether you agree to my proposal?</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_33">So many years have now elapsed, in the vain search for a publisher,</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_34">that we should be wrong if we did not sieze this good opportunity.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_35">In the opinion of people here whom I consulted today, the Italian</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_36">edition would not interfere with an English one.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_37">4) Miss <persName ref="gnd-124986242">Yates</persName>: I am glad to hear from you that no delay will be</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_38">caused by her contribution. Please tell herthat I should be delighted</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_39">if it could be inserted. It certainly would be a pity if pressure</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_40">of other work prevented her from letting us have these few pages in</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_41">time for the Italian translation. In case she should not be able to</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_42">complete it, I would try to revise the original chapter on English</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_43">literature myself, perhaps with the help of a colleague. Needless</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_44">to say, I should be most reluctant to do so.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_45">II.Galenus proofs: As you will remember, I have at the time--i.e.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_46">at Mr. Blunt's departure--taken over the whole correspondence with</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_47">the printers, at <persName ref="gnd-118804898">Saxl</persName>'s request. Mr. Walzer knows this, and I am glad</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_48">that you replied to him in this sense. Actually, the mere reading of</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_49">Father Lator's letter should have shown him that his proposal is non-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_50">sensical. The Director of the Imprimerie --please look at his latter</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_51">--made statements to Lator, which Mr. W. knows to be incorrect. In</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_52">order to guard against new mistakes, we have to see the proofs our-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_53">selves; the only way in which Mr. W. can help is to refrain from making</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_54">any new alterations, and to let us have the proofs quickly.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_55">As to further steps with regard to <placeName ref="geo-276781">Beirut</placeName>, <persName ref="gnd-1029912939">Lotte</persName> will, I presume,</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_56">talk to you during your next stay in London, in the coming week; I</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_57">wrote her about it.</l>
					</lg>
				</p>
			</div>
		</body>
	</text>
